================================================================================
[2026-04-26] Run #5 result — FAILED (same chocophlan error; root cause: stale
                                     Batch-managed merged launch template)
================================================================================

profile_function failed on both samples with the SAME error as run #4:
  CRITICAL ERROR: The directory provided for the ChocoPhlAn database at
  /mnt/dbs/chocophlan_v4_alpha/ does not exist.

But the worker provisioning came from DIFFERENT launch templates than expected.
This is the surprise: AWS Batch's internal LT merging.

Investigation
-------------
Run-5 workers (i-0691d68cb529d0fc4, i-0cf5db89e17e600bf) report tag
aws:ec2launchtemplate:id =
  lt-01d1dc88e9d17dafa  (OnDemand wrapper, name: Batch-lt-e6beaf02-...-rev-2)
  lt-0e794f64e845bb67d  (Spot wrapper,    name: Batch-lt-1c8bf6c4-...-rev-2)
Both launched from the wrapper LTs at version 1.

These are NOT the customer LT we updated. Customer LT lt-0d9193dd0f66d68ee
was correctly bumped to v9 by the CFN deploy and contains the sync block
(verified with `describe-launch-template-versions ... v9`).

The CE configurations still point at lt-0d9193dd0f66d68ee with version=$Latest:
  OnDemandComputeEnvironme-BlIl26JdB3ef8RMS  ->  lt-0d9193dd0f66d68ee/$Latest
  SpotComputeEnvironment-Eyi8eJp5FEi4DwVk    ->  lt-0d9193dd0f66d68ee/$Latest

So why are workers launching from `Batch-lt-*-rev-2` instead?

Root cause: Batch-managed merged launch templates
-------------------------------------------------
When a CE references a customer LT, AWS Batch creates an internal "merged"
launch template that combines our properties (userdata, EBS, instance type)
with Batch's required infrastructure (ECS instance profile, Batch tags, etc.).
This merged LT is what Batch actually launches workers from, NOT the customer
LT directly.

The merged LT is minted at CE creation time and re-minted only when the CE
itself is mutated (state toggle, instance-type change, allocation-strategy
change, etc.). A bump to the customer LT version does NOT trigger a re-merge.
The "rev-2" suffix on the wrapper LT name suggests Batch already re-merged
once previously, but before today's stack update.

So today's CFN deploy successfully:
  - bumped customer LT v8 -> v9 with the /mnt/dbs sync block
  - updated EcsInstanceRole policy with S3 read on cjb-gutz-s3-demo
But did NOT cause Batch to refresh its merged wrappers, so workers continued
launching with the v8-equivalent userdata (no sync).

Fix path
--------
Cycle each CE state DISABLED -> ENABLED. This forces Batch to drop the merged
wrapper and re-mint it from the current customer LT $Latest (= v9 = has sync
block). No running jobs in the queue, so no disruption.

  for CE in OnDemandComputeEnvironme-BlIl26JdB3ef8RMS \
            SpotComputeEnvironment-Eyi8eJp5FEi4DwVk; do
    aws batch update-compute-environment --compute-environment "$CE" \
        --state DISABLED --region us-east-2
  done
  # wait for DISABLED to apply
  for CE in OnDemandComputeEnvironme-BlIl26JdB3ef8RMS \
            SpotComputeEnvironment-Eyi8eJp5FEi4DwVk; do
    aws batch update-compute-environment --compute-environment "$CE" \
        --state ENABLED --region us-east-2
  done

Side note for future Pull Requests / docs
-----------------------------------------
The CFN deploy procedure in infra/readme.md should warn that any change to
the worker LT userdata requires a CE state-cycle afterward, otherwise the
update silently has no effect on newly-spawned workers. This is a known
AWS Batch wart, easy to lose hours to (we just did).

